[[File:China Universities Map.png|thumb|500px|Map showing major universities in Mainland China. Universities of Project 985 are marked in blue (C-9 league schools are marked in red and all of them are Project 985 schools too.)]] '''Project 985''' ({{zh|c=985工程|p= Jiǔbāwǔ gōngchéng}}) is a project that was first announced by CPC General secretary and Chinese President [[Jiang Zemin]] at the 100th anniversary of Peking University on May 4, 1998, to promote the development and reputation of the [[Higher education in China|Chinese higher education system]] by founding world-class universities in the 21st century.<ref>[http://www.ed.ac.uk/about/edinburgh-global/partnerships/region/focus-china/resources-information/universities-china/project-985 Project 985,The University of Edinburgh]</ref> The name derives from the date of the announcement, May 1998, or 98/5 according to the Chinese [[calendar date#Date format|date format]].<ref name="intro">{{cite web |url=http://www.chinaeducenter.com/en/cedu/ceduproject211.php |title=Project 211 and 985 |work=China Education Center Ltd. |accessdate=2010-08-28}}</ref> The project involves both national and local governments allocating large amounts of funding to certain universities<ref name="projectInfo">{{cite web |url=http://baike.baidu.com/view/59436.htm |title=985工程 |accessdate=2010-08-28}}</ref> in order to build new research centers, improve facilities, hold international conferences, attract world-renowned faculty and visiting scholars, and help Chinese faculty attend conferences abroad.<ref name="fundingUse"/>
In 2009, the original 9 founding member universities of Project 985 formed the [[C9 League]],<ref name="fundingUse">{{cite web |url=http://www.wes.org/ewenr/06oct/practical.htm |title=International Rankings and Chinese Higher Education Reform |work=World Education News and Reviews |accessdate=2010-08-28}}</ref> which is referred to as the Chinese equivalent of the US [[Ivy League]].<ref name="C9League">{{cite web |url=http://xjtunews.xjtu.edu.cn/zhxw/2009-10/1255091987d24517.shtml |title=9所首批"985工程"建设高校签订《一流大学人才培养合作与交流协议书》 |accessdate=2009-10-09 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091015052830/http://xjtunews.xjtu.edu.cn/zhxw/2009-10/1255091987d24517.shtml |archivedate=2009-10-15 |df= }}</ref> By the end of the second phase of the project, 39 universities were sponsored. It was announced in 2011 that the project has closed its doors, and no more new schools will be able to join in.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agile-news.com/news-493249-Ministry-of-Education:-no-new-211-985-project-of-the-school.html |title=Ministry of Education: no new "211" "985" project of the school |accessdate=2011-12-30}}</ref>
In September 2017, a related plan called the [[Double First Class University Plan]] was announced.<ref name="people.cn">{{cite news |url=http://en.people.cn/n3/2017/0921/c90000-9272101.html |title=China to develop 42 world-class universities | work=People's Daily |date= 21 September 2017}}</ref><ref name="China Daily">{{Cite web |url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/opinion/2017-09/25/content_32446664.htm |title=双一流大学 (shuāngyīliú dàxué): Double top university plan |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925043627/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/opinion/2017-09/25/content_32446664.htm |archivedate=2017-09-25 |df= }}</ref> It was unclear whether this plan represents a new way of ranking universities in China,<ref name="people.cn"/> or replaces [[Project 211]] and Project 985.<ref name="China Daily"/>
